Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}. Quarter @lime{1}. Core, deseed, and dice @green bell pepper{1} into ½-inch pieces.

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a drizzle of @oil{}, and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{3%tablespoon} with lime juice to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper, salt, and pepper; cook until just softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add another drizzle of oil to pan. Add @ground beef{10%ounce}, half the @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit}, half the @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest of each later), salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat.

> If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place, seam sides down, in an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch baking dish for 4 servings) or an #ovenproof pan{}.

In a #liquid measuring cup{} or #bowl{}, combine ½ cup water (¾ cup for 4 servings), @tomato paste{1%unit}, remaining Tex-Mex paste, and remaining Southwest Spice Blend.

Pour sauce over enchiladas to thoroughly coat. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese has melted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Top enchiladas with lime crema and pico de gallo. Divide between plates and serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.